# LiVEiT® Typography

Typography is a core element of the LiVEiT® visual identity.

Clear, consistent typography improves readability, accessibility and recognition across every LiVEiT® project.

The goal is to present information in a structured and professional manner while maintaining a modern visual appearance.

---

# Typography Principles

The LiVEiT® Framework follows five typography principles:

* Readability
* Consistency
* Simplicity
* Accessibility
* Scalability

Typography should support the content rather than compete with it.

---

# Font Selection

LiVEiT® does not require a proprietary typeface.

Official projects should use modern, highly legible fonts that are widely supported across operating systems and web browsers.

Recommended font families include:

| Font            | Typical Use                            |
| --------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| Arial           | Default user interfaces                |
| Helvetica       | Professional print and digital layouts |
| Inter           | Modern web applications                |
| System UI Fonts | Native desktop and mobile applications |

Projects should select one primary typeface and use it consistently throughout the interface.

---

# Font Hierarchy

A clear hierarchy helps users understand information quickly.

Typical hierarchy:

| Element     | Purpose                |
| ----------- | ---------------------- |
| H1          | Primary page title     |
| H2          | Major section heading  |
| H3          | Subsection heading     |
| H4          | Minor heading          |
| Body Text   | Primary content        |
| Caption     | Supporting information |
| Button Text | Interactive elements   |

Heading levels should follow a logical document structure.

---

# Font Weight

Use font weight to establish emphasis rather than relying on colour alone.

Recommended usage:

| Weight    | Purpose          |
| --------- | ---------------- |
| Regular   | Body content     |
| Medium    | Interface labels |
| Semi-Bold | Section headings |
| Bold      | Primary headings |

Excessive use of bold text should be avoided.

---

# Font Size

Typography should remain comfortable to read across all screen sizes.

General guidance:

| Element     | Suggested Size |
| ----------- | -------------- |
| H1          | 36–48 px       |
| H2          | 28–36 px       |
| H3          | 22–28 px       |
| Body        | 16–18 px       |
| Caption     | 12–14 px       |
| Button Text | 15–18 px       |

These values may be adjusted to suit individual platforms while maintaining visual consistency.

---

# Line Height

Adequate spacing improves readability.

Recommended line heights:

* Body text: 1.5–1.7
* Headings: 1.2–1.3
* Captions: 1.4–1.5

Avoid overly compressed or excessively spaced text.

---

# Text Alignment

Unless a specific design requires otherwise:

* Left-align paragraphs.
* Use centred text sparingly.
* Avoid fully justified text for digital interfaces.

Consistent alignment improves readability.

---

# Colour

Typography should always maintain sufficient contrast with its background.

Recommended practice:

* Dark text on light backgrounds.
* Light text on dark backgrounds.
* Accent colours only for emphasis.

Text should remain readable under all viewing conditions.

---

# Accessibility

Typography should support users with a wide range of visual abilities.

Official LiVEiT® projects should:

* Maintain sufficient colour contrast.
* Avoid excessively small text.
* Use clear letter spacing.
* Avoid decorative fonts for body content.
* Ensure text scales appropriately on different devices.

Typography should comply with recognised accessibility standards wherever practical.

---

# Responsive Design

Typography should adapt gracefully across:

* Desktop computers
* Tablets
* Mobile devices
* Large displays

Responsive scaling should preserve the established visual hierarchy.

---

# Code and Documentation

Technical documentation should use monospaced fonts for code examples.

Recommended options include:

* Consolas
* Menlo
* Monaco
* SF Mono
* Courier New

Code blocks should remain visually distinct from body text.

---

# Consistency

A limited number of font families should be used throughout the LiVEiT® ecosystem.

Maintaining consistent typography strengthens the overall identity of the framework and improves the user experience.

---

# Future Development

Typography guidance may evolve as the LiVEiT® Framework expands to new platforms and products.

Any additions should remain consistent with the principles of clarity, accessibility and simplicity that define the LiVEiT® brand.
